SIMPLE: neurotic
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Neurotic
<hw>Neu*rot"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr.
<grk>ney^ron</grk> nerve.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to
the nerves; seated in the nerves; nervous; <as>as, a <ex>neurotic</ex>
disease</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Useful in disorders of, or affecting, the
nerves.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to neurosis{2}; characteristic of
neurosis{2}; caused by neurosis{2}.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Neurotic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Neurotic
<hw>Neu*rot"ic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A disease seated in
the nerves.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Any toxic agent whose action is
mainly directed to the great nerve centers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <ex>Neurotics</ex> as a class include all those poisons
whose main action is upon the brain and spinal cord. They may be divided
into three orders: (<it>a</it>) <xex>Cerebral neurotics</xex>, or those
which affect the brain only. (<it>b</it>) <xex>Spinal neurotics</xex>,
or <xex>tetanics</xex>, those which affect the spinal cord. (<it>c</it>)
<xex>Cerebro-spinal neurotics</xex>, or those which affect both brain
and spinal cord.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A person afflicted with a neurosis{2}.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Neurotome</ent>⟦br⟧
